  "original_title": "5 \u0b87\u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc2\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0bae\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bcb\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bbf",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "QR system failure at 5 locations",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Power and Energy Minister Kanchana Wijesekara said that the National Fuel Permit or QR code system has been tested successfully at 20 locations across the country, but the pilot project could not be implemented at 5 locations.",
        "The Minister stated that the reasons for this were non-delivery of pre-production, delay in delivery of pre-production and delay in delivery and distribution.",
        "Although the minister had pointed out the above issues in his Twitter post published today (24), he further said,",
        "He mentioned that this system has been tested at 25 locations by the Sri Lanka Petroleum Corporation and successfully completed at 20 locations nationwide under which 4,708 vehicles have been refueled.",
        "The minister also indicated that the pilot program of providing fuel under QR code will be implemented in five other places in the next two days.",
        "Meanwhile, 35 lakh 23,729 people have registered till Saturday (23) night to get fuel using the QR code system."
      ],
